  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>bdi vs bdo</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/bdi-bdo-comparison.html" url="bdi-bdo-comparison.html" title="bdi vs bdo" shadow></browser-window>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Element</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
          <th>Direction</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Isolate &mdash; let the browser detect direction</td>
          <td>Defaults to <code>auto</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;bdo&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Override &mdash; force a specific direction</td>
          <td>Requires <code>dir="rtl"</code> or <code>dir="ltr"</code></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Attributes</h2>
    <p>Supports <a href="/docs/elements/native/states/">global attributes</a>. The <code>dir</code> attribute defaults to <code>auto</code> on <code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code> elements, meaning the direction is determined by the element's content.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS</h2>
    <code-block language="css" label="bdi CSS (browser default)">{{ bdiCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>VB does not add additional styling. The element's value is purely in its Unicode isolation behavior.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <p><code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code> has no special accessibility role. It affects visual rendering only. Screen readers read the content in logical order regardless of visual direction.</p>
  </section>

